International Women's Day 2025: Top 100+ wishes, messages, quotes, slogans, images, WhatsApp status, and Instagram captions for all the ladies

International Women's Day is just around the corner celebrated annually on March 8. Here we have created a list of International Women's Day wishes, quotes, and images that you can share with your mother, wife, sister, daughter, girlfriend and all the ladies you know. You will also get trending WhatsApp statuses & Instagram captions for Women's Day.

Bhupinder SinghUpdated: Mar 08, 2025, 09:51 IST
15 min read
Credit: Pixabay

International Women's Day is celebrated every year on March 8 to honour the achievements of women in all fields. It is a day to recognise their contributions to society, raise awareness about gender equality, and promote women's empowerment. This global celebration also highlights the need for equal opportunities and rights for women in social, economic, cultural, and political spheres.

Every year, International Women's Day has a theme to focus on specific issues related to gender equality. The theme for International Women's Day 2025, set by the United Nations (UN), is “For ALL Women and Girls: Rights. Equality. Empowerment.” This theme reminds us of the importance of supporting all women and girls to create a more equal world.

Additionally, the official International Women's Day website has introduced the theme “Accelerate Action.” This encourages individuals, organisations, and governments to take meaningful steps to remove barriers and promote women's rights.

If you are searching for the perfect wishes, quotes, messages, WhatsApp status, and Instagram captions to share with the incredible women in your life, we have compiled a list for you.

    "15% ROI 6 Months" means that an investment is expected to generate a return of 15% over a period of six months. ROI stands for "Return on Investment," which is a measure used to evaluate the efficiency or profitability of an investment. In this context, if you invest a certain amount, after six months, you would expect to earn 15% more than what you initially invested. For example, if you invested $1,000, a 15% ROI would result in a return of $150, making your total amount $1,150 after six months.

    Recommended Actions:

    1. Update Dependencies:
      • First, try to run the following command:
        npm audit fix
        This command will automatically update the packages to the latest safe versions that do not introduce breaking changes.
    2. Use --force (With Caution):
      • If you are willing to accept breaking changes (which often happen when major version updates are performed), you can run:
        npm audit fix --force
      • Warning: This may lead to incompatibilities or bugs in your project, especially if the major version changes involve breaking changes in libraries.
    3. Manually Review Dependencies:
      • After running the automatic fixes, review your package.json and package-lock.json (or npm-shrinkwrap.json) to understand how the dependency tree has changed.
      • In some cases, you might need to manually check the release notes of major version upgrades to understand any breaking changes.
    4. Test Your Application:
      • After applying updates, run your tests and verify that your application is functioning as expected. This step is crucial especially if you performed a --force operation.
    5. Consider Alternative Packages:
      • If certain packages are not being maintained and are consistently causing vulnerabilities, consider looking for alternative libraries that provide similar functionality but are more actively maintained.
    6. Stay Updated:
      • Regularly use npm audit and check for updates to your packages to avoid accumulating multiple vulnerabilities in the future.

    Conclusion:

    Addressing vulnerabilities is crucial for the security and stability of your application. Always ensure to back up your work and thoroughly test the application after making dependency changes.

    It looks like you're dealing with a significant number of vulnerabilities in your Node.js project. Here's a breakdown of how to handle these issues:

    Steps to Fix Vulnerabilities

    1. Backup Your Project: Before making any changes, create a backup of your project. This is important in case something goes wrong during the updates.
    2. Evaluate Breaking Changes: Running npm audit fix --force will install newer versions of packages that may introduce breaking changes—especially with react-scripts. You need to check if these package updates are compatible with your codebase before proceeding. Review the changelogs of the major libraries for any breaking changes.
    3. Run Audit Fix: Start by trying the command that won't apply breaking changes: 
      npm audit fix
      This will attempt to fix vulnerabilities without installing major version upgrades.
    4. Review and Manually Update Dependencies: If vulnerabilities remain after running the previous command, check which packages are still vulnerable. Start investigating whether those can be updated manually with: 
      npm update <package-name>
    5. Force Fix for Critical Issues: If the vulnerabilities cannot be resolved without applying breaking changes, you may consider: 
      npm audit fix --force
      Keep in mind that this may update react-scripts to version 5.0.1, which includes breaking changes. Review your application after this update. You can also consider testing in a separate branch or isolated environment.
    6. Test Your Application Thoroughly: After making these updates, run your application and execute existing tests to ensure everything works as expected. Address any breaking changes introduced by updates.
    7. Consider Alternative Libraries: If a library has been outdated or poorly maintained (which is common with security vulnerabilities), look for more robust alternatives. For example, if request is vulnerable, consider using axios instead.
    8. Regularly Check for Vulnerabilities: Make it a habit to regularly run npm audit and stay updated on dependencies.
    9. Document Changes: Keep a log of changes you've made for future reference.

    Example of Upgrading Dependencies

    To upgrade the `react-scripts` package, you can specify the desired version in your `package.json`: 
    {
  "scripts": {
    "start": "react-scripts start",
    "build": "react-scripts build",
    "test": "react-scripts test",
    "eject": "react-scripts eject"
  },
  "dependencies": {
    "react-scripts": "5.0.1", // Upgrade to the latest version
    // other dependencies
  }
}
    Then run: 
    npm install

    Conclusion

    Addressing vulnerabilities is an ongoing task. Prioritize critical and high-severity issues, and regularly update your dependencies. Be cautious with updates that may break code and ensure robust testing afterward. If there are further issues or you encounter specific errors after making changes, feel free to seek help with details about the problems you're facing.
